<body>
<div class="container">

  <header>
    <div class="eyebrow">Listening lesson · Teacher cue sheet</div>
    <h1>Why one person<br><span class="accent">can't be everything</span></h1>
    <div class="subtitle">A guided in-class listen with Esther Perel × Oprah, designed to adapt across levels.</div>
    <div class="episode-meta">
      <div><strong>Source:</strong> The Oprah Podcast, 26 May 2026</div>
      <div><strong>Total runtime:</strong> 58 min</div>
      <div><strong>You'll use:</strong> ~13 min of audio across 3 segments</div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- === Orientation === -->
  <section>
    <div class="section-label">How to use this</div>
    <div class="orientation">
      <div class="orientation-title">Open this alongside Spotify; let the segment timestamps drive the flow.</div>
      <p class="prose">Three segments build a single arc — <em>how relationships have changed</em>, then <em>the core thesis (one person can't be everything)</em>, then <em>what to do about it</em>. Around 5 minutes of audio each, with pause-and-ask prompts inside so you can interrupt at natural moments and direct the conversation without losing momentum.</p>
      <p class="prose">For <strong>B1</strong> students, play in shorter bursts (30–60 seconds at a time), pre-teach the vocabulary thoroughly, and lean on the B1-scaffold sentence frames in each segment. If comprehension breaks down, stop pushing — switch to discussing the topic without the audio. Esther's pace is fast and her vocabulary is sophisticated, so for true beginners this podcast is a stretch.</p>
      <p class="prose">For <strong>B2 and above</strong>, play each segment in one go, then use the pause prompts as your tool kit for the discussion that follows. C1-stretch prompts push toward more abstract or contested territory if the student is ready for it.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- === Warm-up === -->
  <section>
    <div class="section-label">Before pressing play · 5 min</div>
    <h2>Warm-up — set the topic.</h2>
    <p class="prose">Ask one or two of these to prime the theme before any audio plays. Their answers also tell you where they are emotionally on the topic — useful calibration.</p>
    <ul class="warmup-list">
      <li>When you were growing up, what did people in your family or culture say about love?</li>
      <li>What does the perfect partner look like to a 20-year-old? What does it look like to a 50-year-old? Is the picture the same?</li>
      <li>If you have a partner — what do you ask of them that perhaps your grandparents wouldn't have asked of theirs?</li>
      <li>Is it possible to ask too much of one person? Where's the line?</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- === SEGMENT A === -->
  <section class="segment">
    <div class="segment-header">
      <div class="segment-letter">A</div>
      <div class="segment-title-wrap">
        <div class="segment-meta">Segment A — diagnosis</div>
        <div class="segment-title">How relationships have changed</div>
      </div>
      <div class="segment-time"><strong>5:12 – 10:32</strong>≈ 5 min 20 s</div>
    </div>

    <div class="block">
      <div class="block-label">Topic snapshot</div>
      <div class="block-body">Esther wrote <em>Mating in Captivity</em> 20 years ago. She and Oprah reflect on what's changed between 2006 and 2026 — and the paradox at the heart of modern life: we're more "connected" than ever and lonelier than ever.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="block vocab">
      <div class="block-label">Pre-listen vocabulary</div>
      <dl>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>intimacy</dt><dd>— closeness, especially emotional closeness</dd></div>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>accessibility</dt><dd>— being available, reachable, present in a real way</dd></div>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>disconnection</dt><dd>— feeling apart, distant, separated</dd></div>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>paradox</dt><dd>— when two opposite things are true at the same time</dd></div>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>to erode</dt><dd>— to slowly wear away (often used about trust, intimacy)</dd></div>
      </dl>
    </div>

    <div class="block listen-for">
      <div class="block-label">Listen for</div>
      <div class="listen-for-text">Esther contrasts being <em>connected</em> with being <em>accessible</em>. What's the difference she's pointing at?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="block pause-prompts">
      <div class="pause-label"><span class="pause-icon">II</span>Pause &amp; ask</div>
      <ul class="pause-list">
        <li><span class="pause-when">When she names what's changed</span>She said relationships in 2026 are different from 2006. Did you catch the main change? Do you see it in your own life?</li>
        <li><span class="pause-when">When she mentions phones / screens</span>How does what she's describing show up in your relationships with a partner, friends, or family?</li>
        <li><span class="pause-when">When she says "more connected, less ___"</span>What's the difference between being <em>available</em> and being <em>present</em>? Can you think of someone close to you who is one but not the other?</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="block check">
      <div class="block-label">Quick comprehension check</div>
      <ol>
        <li>What word does Esther use for the contradiction of modern life?</li>
        <li>What's the basic contrast she draws between then and now?</li>
        <li>What kinds of technology or behaviour does she mention as part of the problem?</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="block discuss">
      <div class="block-label">Discussion</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Do you agree we're more connected and less accessible than 20 years ago?</li>
        <li>Is the picture different in France from what you know of other cultures?</li>
        <li>What's one specific moment from this week where you noticed this in your own life?</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="levels">
      <div class="level-card b1">
        <div class="level-tag">B1 — softer entry</div>
        <div class="level-body">Use the sentence frame: <em>"Yes / no, I agree because in my life ___. For example, ___."</em> Keep questions concrete and personal; resist abstract ones.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="level-card c1">
        <div class="level-tag">C1 — push further</div>
        <div class="level-body">Is "more connected, less accessible" actually new — or has every generation had its version of this complaint? Are we doing this to ourselves?</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- === SEGMENT B === -->
  <section class="segment">
    <div class="segment-header">
      <div class="segment-letter">B</div>
      <div class="segment-title-wrap">
        <div class="segment-meta">Segment B — the core thesis</div>
        <div class="segment-title">One person can't be everything</div>
      </div>
      <div class="segment-time"><strong>17:30 – 22:50</strong>≈ 5 min 20 s</div>
    </div>

    <div class="block">
      <div class="block-label">Topic snapshot</div>
      <div class="block-body">Esther's central thesis. In the past, the <em>village</em> provided most of our emotional needs — friends, neighbours, extended family, community. Today, we ask one person — our romantic partner — to be everything: best friend, lover, intellectual equal, co-parent, therapist, business partner. No one person can carry that load. The romantic myth that "the one" exists makes the burden heavier still.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="block vocab">
      <div class="block-label">Pre-listen vocabulary</div>
      <dl>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>the village</dt><dd>— a small community where everyone knows everyone (here, used as a metaphor for the network of people who used to support us)</dd></div>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>demands</dt><dd>— what you ask of someone or expect from them</dd></div>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>"the one"</dt><dd>— a cultural idea of a single perfect soulmate</dd></div>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>myth</dt><dd>— a widely-believed story that may not be true</dd></div>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>burden</dt><dd>— a heavy responsibility or weight</dd></div>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>to outsource</dt><dd>— to give a task to someone else to handle</dd></div>
      </dl>
    </div>

    <div class="block listen-for">
      <div class="block-label">Listen for</div>
      <div class="listen-for-text">Esther talks about what we used to get from a "village" — and what we now demand from one partner. Can you catch the list?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="block pause-prompts">
      <div class="pause-label"><span class="pause-icon">II</span>Pause &amp; ask</div>
      <ul class="pause-list">
        <li><span class="pause-when">When she lists what we ask of partners</span>Could you make your own list — what do you ask of your partner or closest people? Best friend, therapist, business partner — which roles are on your list?</li>
        <li><span class="pause-when">When she mentions the "village" or community</span>Who is "the village" in your life — friends, family, neighbours, colleagues? Is it bigger or smaller than it was ten years ago?</li>
        <li><span class="pause-when">When she talks about the love myth or "the one"</span>What did you grow up believing about love? Was there a fairy-tale version in your family or culture?</li>
        <li><span class="pause-when">When she names something as a "burden"</span>Have you ever felt that you were asking too much of one person — or that someone was asking too much of you?</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="block check">
      <div class="block-label">Quick comprehension check</div>
      <ol>
        <li>What did the "village" used to provide that we now expect from one partner?</li>
        <li>What does Esther say about the myth of "the one"?</li>
        <li>What's the consequence — what happens when one person is asked to be everything?</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="block discuss">
      <div class="block-label">Discussion</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Do you think the French version of romantic love is different from the American version Esther is describing?</li>
        <li>Who, besides your partner if you have one, "is" things for you — your humour, your honesty, your challenge? Where do those people come from?</li>
        <li>Is "the one" a useful idea or a harmful one?</li>
        <li>What have you stopped asking of a partner over the years — and where does that need go now?</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="levels">
      <div class="level-card b1">
        <div class="level-tag">B1 — softer entry</div>
        <div class="level-body">Use the sentence frame: <em>"For me, my ___ is ___. My ___ is ___. But my partner is mostly my ___."</em> Visual aid: write the list of roles on screen (lover, best friend, co-parent, therapist…) and have her point to who in her life plays each one.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="level-card c1">
        <div class="level-tag">C1 — push further</div>
        <div class="level-body">Esther's argument is that one partner can't be everything. The counter-argument: but isn't intimate love supposed to be all-encompassing? Where do you land? How much of this conversation is cultural, and how much is universal human nature?</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- === SEGMENT C === -->
  <section class="segment">
    <div class="segment-header">
      <div class="segment-letter">C</div>
      <div class="segment-title-wrap">
        <div class="segment-meta">Segment C — the reframe</div>
        <div class="segment-title">What to look for instead</div>
      </div>
      <div class="segment-time"><strong>22:50 – 25:30</strong>≈ 2 min 40 s</div>
    </div>

    <div class="block">
      <div class="block-label">Topic snapshot</div>
      <div class="block-body">If one person can't be everything, what does that mean practically — for how we choose a partner, and how we stay with one? Esther's reframe of the question.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="block vocab">
      <div class="block-label">Pre-listen vocabulary</div>
      <dl>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>compatible</dt><dd>— well-matched, work well together</dd></div>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>chemistry</dt><dd>— instant attraction, spark</dd></div>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>maintenance</dt><dd>— the ongoing care needed to keep something working</dd></div>
        <div class="vocab-row"><dt>realistic</dt><dd>— based on what's actually true, not on fantasy</dd></div>
      </dl>
    </div>

    <div class="block listen-for">
      <div class="block-label">Listen for</div>
      <div class="listen-for-text">What does Esther say matters more than "finding the right person" in a long-term relationship?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="block pause-prompts">
      <div class="pause-label"><span class="pause-icon">II</span>Pause &amp; ask</div>
      <ul class="pause-list">
        <li><span class="pause-when">When she names what to look for</span>What's on your own list of what makes a partner work over time? Has the list changed as you've got older?</li>
        <li><span class="pause-when">When she talks about ongoing work</span>People often say "a relationship is work." Is that romantic, or is it sad?</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="block check">
      <div class="block-label">Quick comprehension check</div>
      <ol>
        <li>What's Esther's reframe — what matters more than "finding the one"?</li>
        <li>What kind of skill or quality does she emphasise?</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="block discuss">
      <div class="block-label">Discussion</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Is being a "good partner" something you're born with, or something you learn?</li>
        <li>Have you ever changed your idea of what makes a good relationship? When, and why?</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="levels">
      <div class="level-card b1">
        <div class="level-tag">B1 — softer entry</div>
        <div class="level-body">Sentence frame: <em>"For me, the most important thing in a relationship is ___, because ___."</em></div>
      </div>
      <div class="level-card c1">
        <div class="level-tag">C1 — push further</div>
        <div class="level-body">Esther focuses on what we ask <em>from</em> partners. What do you think we should be asking <em>of ourselves</em> in a relationship?</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- === Wrap-up production === -->
  <section>
    <div class="section-label">Closing · production · 8–10 min</div>
    <h2>Wrap-up — pick one, speak for 2 minutes.</h2>
    <p class="prose">All three prompts work whether the student is single, partnered, married, or divorced — designed not to exclude anyone. Let them choose. Note vocabulary they reach for and any structures they avoid.</p>
    <div class="wrapup">
      <div class="wrapup-title">Talk to me for two minutes.</div>
      <div class="wrapup-intro">Pick the one that pulls you.</div>
      <ul class="wrapup-list">
        <li>Describe your "village" — who do you depend on, and for what? Be specific.</li>
        <li>What's one thing you've stopped expecting from your partner or closest person — and where does that need go now?</li>
        <li>Was there a moment when you realised the romantic fairy-tale wasn't true? What happened?</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- === Take-home === -->
  <section>
    <div class="takehome">
      <div class="takehome-label">Optional take-home</div>
      <div class="takehome-text">Choose one of the three wrap-up questions and write 100–150 words in response. Bring it to our next session.</div>
    </div>
  </section>

